{"result": "{\n    \"title\": \"Chapter X: High-Low Method and Its Applications\",\n    \"summary\": \"Chapter X delves into the High-Low Method, a technique used to estimate fixed and variable costs by analyzing the highest and lowest levels of activity. The chapter covers the methodology in detail, including its application in various scenarios such as estimating electricity costs and preparing flexible budgets. Key concepts include the calculation of variable overhead costs and the relationship between the High-Low Method and other analytical techniques like regression and time series analysis. The chapter also includes practical examples and quizzes to reinforce learning outcomes.\",\n    \"rating\": 8.5,\n    \"rating_explanation\": \"The chapter's content is highly significant due to its practical applications in cost estimation and budgeting, which are essential skills in financial management.\",\n    \"findings\": [\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"The High-Low Method is a fundamental technique for cost estimation.\",\n            \"explanation\": \"The High-Low Method is a technique used to calculate costs by analyzing the highest and lowest levels of activity and their associated costs. It is employed to estimate the fixed and variable components of a cost by examining these extreme activity levels and their corresponding costs. This method involves selecting the costs associated with the highest and lowest levels of activity and assuming a straight-line relationship between these two points. By doing so, it helps in estimating the fixed and variable elements of a semi-variable cost, enabling more accurate forecasts of costs [Data: Concepts (850)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Application of the High-Low Method in estimating electricity costs.\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Tomkins Co uses the High-Low Method to estimate the fixed and variable components of electricity costs based on direct labour hours. This application h